    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-11-17T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-11-17T17:00:00-05:00" n="766"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d766">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.59A31/74a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Iceland</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-11-17T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 17, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>124. Public announcement of intention to negotiate a trade agreement with Iceland
                    was issued today.<note n="23" xml:id="d766fn23">For list of products on which
                        the United States agreed to consider granting concessions, see Department of
                        State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, November 22, 1941, pp.
                        411–412.</note> Listed below are the paragraph numbers of the United States
                    Tariff Act of 1930<note n="24" xml:id="d766fn24">46 Stat 590.</note> which
                    include <pb facs="0785" n="773" xml:id="pg_773"/> the items on which the United
                    States has announced its intention to consider granting concessions to Iceland.
                    Following the numbers are listed the products of particular interest to Iceland
                    which are to be considered under the respective tariff paragraphs. 717(<hi
                        rend="italic">c</hi>), mainly dried, unsalted fish, including “stockfish”;
                        718(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>), mainly such Scandinavian specialties as
                    herring fillets in oil, or in oil and sauce; 718 (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>),
                    mainly such Scandinavian canned fish specialties as smoked herring fillets and
                    boiled codfish balls; 719(2), mainly dried and green-salted cod; 719(4), salted
                    herring of different kinds of cut and cure; 720(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) (6),
                    mainly smoked lake fish; 721(<hi rend="italic">d</hi>), fish roe other than
                    sturgeon; 1685 and 1780, fish scrap and meal for fertilizer and for other than
                    human consumption; 1730(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>), cod oil and cod-liver oil;
                        1519(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>), dressed lamb and sheep skins.</p>
                <p>The closing date for submission of briefs is December 8, and a public hearing
                    will be held on December 15.</p>
                <p>Further instructions will follow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
